    en: "Most permanent New York civil service employees with at least 5 years of continuous service cannot be disciplined or fired without formal due process under Civil Service Law Section 75. The agency must serve written charges, hold a hearing before an impartial hearing officer, and issue a written decision. The employee has the right to counsel, to confront witnesses, to present evidence, and to judicial review under CPLR Article 78. Alternative disciplinary procedures may exist under collective bargaining agreements (Taylor Law, Civil Service Law Article 14). Probationary employees, non-competitive class, and exempt employees have more limited protections. The procedural rigor is designed to prevent arbitrary or politically-motivated firings in the merit-based civil service."
